#h(1em)As an urban planner, I would argue that Tsukuba fails to achieve the true "marriage" of town and country, resulting in mere coexistence without connection.
To start with, the strict zoning creates a sharp divide between the modern urban center and the surrounding agricultural land, rather than blending them. In addition, there is little social interaction between the new urban residents and the traditional local farming communities. On top of that, the city’s economy operates independently of the local agriculture, meaning residents rarely consume what is grown right next door.
That’s why, even though the city sits beside the countryside, it suggests that Howard’s vision was fundamentally unrealistic.

