#h(1em)As an urban planner, I believe Tsukuba Science City is a successful realization of Perry’s Neighborhood Unit theory. First, the extensive network of pedestrian decks and parks allows residents to move through the city without encountering cars. Second, this unique infrastructure perfectly embodies Perry's principle of "Open Spaces," providing accessible recreation areas for every neighborhood. Not only that, the abundance of greenery integrates nature into daily urban life, promoting both physical and mental well-being. All in all, Tsukuba demonstrates that the Neighborhood Unit can create a garden-city environment that prioritizes human health over automobile efficiency.

